                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d547">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">838.51/3375: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Haiti</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Finley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Port-au-Prince</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-07-10T12:00:00-05:00"
                            >July 10, 1937—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 2:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>42. Department’s 24, July 8, 5 p.m. The Department’s views were communicated to
                    Leger this morning. He said he had understood these views to be as I had
                    indicated and that his Government and mine appeared to be in perfect agreement
                    on this subject.</p>
                <p>Regarding his conversations with De la Rue concerning the formulation of a bank
                    plan, he said that in case nothing came of the Eberstadt proposal, he would
                    immediately resume these conversations for he was genuinely anxious to reach an
                    agreement regarding the termination of financial control.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Finley</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
